 This is my test python file:
```python
vertex_shader = """
#version 330

uniform sampler2D position_texture;
uniform sampler2D normal_texture;
uniform sampler2D diffuse_texture;

uniform mat4 modelview = mat4(0.0);
uniform ivec2 texel_pos = ivec2(0);

out vec3 out_position;
out vec3 out_normal;
out float out_temperature;

void main() {
    vec3 vertex_coord_in_camera = texelFetch(position_texture, texel_pos, 0).rgb;
    if (vertex_coord_in_camera.z == 0.0) {
        // A 0.0 z value means we missed the mesh. Just write out 0.0 as the result
        out_position = vec3(0.0);
        out_normal = vec3(0.0);
        out_temperature = 0.0;
    } else {
        // Reverse translations and rotations aligning the point with the original mesh
        out_position = (inverse(modelview) * vec4(vertex_coord_in_camera, 1.0)).xyz;
        out_normal = texelFetch(normal_texture, texel_pos, 0).xyz;
        out_temperature = texelFetch(diffuse_texture, texel_pos, 0).r;
    }
}
"""

if __name__ == '__main__':
    import moderngl

    ctx = moderngl.create_standalone_context()
    program = ctx.program(vertex_shader=vertex_shader)
    print(program._members)

```
after I create a program object by `program =ctx.program(vertex_shader=vertex_shader)`, 
the program._members only contains part of the variables `{'position_texture': <Uniform: 0>, 'modelview': <Uniform: 1>, 'texel_pos': <Uniform: 2>}`.
Since I am new to shader,  all the things that I know is OpenGL will remove the unused variables in shader. 
Thanks, and sorry for my poor english.

